===Proper noun===
{{en-proper noun}}
# The [[chief]] [[river]] of [[central]] [[China]] and the [[third]] [[longest]] [[river]] in the [[world]], [[flow]]ing 6300 [[km]] from the [[Tanggula]] [[mountains|Mountains]] in [[Qinghai]], [[pass]]ing [[Chongqing]], [[Wuhan]], and [[Nanjing]], and [[empty]]ing into the [[East China Sea]] [[beside]] [[Shanghai]].
#* {{quote-book |en |year=1625 |author={{w|Samuel Purchas}} |title=Pvrchas His Pilgrimes |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Purchas_His_Pilgrimes/BuXnOBZpHc8C |volume=III |location=[[London]] |OCLC=219967499 |page=340
|passage=That [[river|Riuer]] of ''[[Nanquin]]'' which I called ('''''Yamſu''''' or) '''''Ianſu''''', the ''[[son|ſonne]] of the Sea'', goeth Northward to ''[[Nanquin]]'', and then returning [[somewhat|ſomewhat]] Southward, runneth into the Sea with great force; [[forty|fortie]] [[miles|myles]] from which it [[passes|paſſeth]] by ''[[Nanquin]]''. And that from hence to [[Peking|''Pequin'']] there might [[be]]e [[passage|paſſage]] by [[river|Riuer]]s, the Kings of ''China'' haue [[derived|deriued]] a large [[channel|Channell]] from this to another [[river|Riuer]], called the '''''Yellow Riuer''''', [[such|ſuch]] being the colour of that troubled water. This is the other famous [[river|Riuer]] of that [[kingdom|Kingdome]], in [[greatness|greatneſſe]] and note, which [[arises|ariſesth]] without the [[kingdom|Kingdome]] to the [[west|Weſt]], out of the [[hill|Hill]] [[Kunlun|''Cunlun'']], conjectured to [[be]]e the [[same|ſame]] whence ''[[Ganges]]'' [[arises|ariſeth]], or one [[near|neere]] to it.}}
#* {{quote-journal |en |date=December 8, 1853 |author={{w|Humphrey Marshall (general)|Humphrey Marshall}} |journal=Documents Relating to the Foreign Relations of the United States with Other Countries |url=https://archive.org/details/unitedstatescon786offigoog/ |issue=37 |year_published=1854 |location=[[Macao]] |publisher=A.O.P. Nicholson |OCLC=270770057 |pages=323-324 |pageurl=https://archive.org/details/unitedstatescon786offigoog/page/n357/
|passage=You will perceive that the British and French commissioners ascend the '''Yangtze''' at pleasure, and ''have the steamers of their respective countries at their disposal''. ''I'' was compelled, for the want of other conveyance, to come hither in a little British steamer which plies between Shanghai and Hong Kong.}}
#* {{quote-journal |en |url=https://archive.org/details/journalofproceed1886phil/ |year=1887 |origdate=October 19, 1886 |author=G. T. Bedell, Thomas H. Vail, B. W. Morris, Geo. F. Seymour, Wm. J. Boone |title=Fourteenth Day's Proceedings |journal=Journal of the Proceedings of the Bishops, Clergy, and Laity of the {{w|Protestant Episcopal Church}} in the United States of America |location=[[Chicago]] |page=99 |pageurl=https://archive.org/details/journalofproceed1886phil/page/n146/
|passage=The Bishop of Shanghai desires that the bounds of his jurisdiction shall be more clearly expressed, and that therefore his title shall hereafter be, "The Bishop of Shanghai, having jurisdiction in the lower valley of '''Yangtze'''." The jurisdiction will be sufficiently large. The '''Yangtze''' River is three thousand miles in length, and the population on its borders numbers one hundred millions. As there are already three Bishops of the Church of England, with a large Missionary force of English Clergy, in that empire, Bishop Boone desires that his jurisdiction be limited to the population on the lower '''Yangtze''', a line of eight hundred miles. }}
#* {{quote-book |en |url=https://archive.org/details/yangtzevalleybey00bird_0/ |year=1900 |title=The Yangtze Valley and Beyond |volume=1 |author={{w|Isabella L. Bird}} |pages=[https://archive.org/details/yangtzevalleybey00bird_0/page/9 9]-[https://archive.org/details/yangtzevalleybey00bird_0/page/10 10]
|passage=It is not till the '''Yangtze''' reaches Sha-shih that its character completely changes. The first note of change is a great embankment, thirty feet high, which protects the region from inundation. Below Sha-shih the vast river becomes mixed up with a network of lakes and rivers, connected by canals, the area of the important [[Dongting|Tungting]] Lake being over 2000 square miles. }}
#* {{quote-book |en |year=1918 |author=J.S. Lee |title=The Geology of China |url=https://etheses.bham.ac.uk/id/eprint/1448/1/Lee1918MSc.pdf |publisher={{w|University of Birmingham}} |OCLC=729577746 |page=320
|passage=Of the northernmost one of these folds, the writer has some faint recollection of seeing the folded strata. They form the hills to the west of [[Hanyang|Han-yung]] and the central ridge across the city of [[Wuchang|Wu-chang]] and extends further east; the west-easterly course of the '''Yang-tze''' below Yang-lo (lat. 30° 30' N.) is in all probability determined by this E-W fold. }}
#* {{quote-book |en |url=https://archive.org/details/china0000tuan/ |year=1969 |title=China |author={{w|Yi-Fu Tuan}} |publisher=Aldine Publishing Company |location=Chicago |page=[https://archive.org/details/china0000tuan/page/22 22]
|passage=Aside from the [[Turfan]] depression in Hsin-chiang ([[Sinkiang]]) province, the hottest part of China lies in the middle and lower '''Yangtze''' Valley. Maximum temperatures of 43°-44°C (110°-112°F) have been recorded in [[Ch'ang-sha]] and [[Nan-ching]].}}
#* {{quote-book |en |url=https://archive.org/details/imperiallibraryi0064wink/ |year=1974 |title=The Imperial Library in Southern Sung China, 1127-1279 : A Study of the Organization and Operation of the Scholarly Agencies of the Central Government |author=John H. Winkelman |page=[https://archive.org/details/imperiallibraryi0064wink/page/12 12]
|passage=Early in the summer of 1127 the emperor was located near the city of [[Nan-ching]] just south of the '''Yangtze''' River. }}
#* {{quote-journal |en |url=https://archive.org/details/sim_free-china-weekly_1982-01-03_23_1/ |date=1982 January 3 |title=News Stories of Year on Peiping Selected |journal=Free China Weekly |volume=XXIII |issue=1 |location=[[Taipei]] |page=3 |pageurl=https://archive.org/details/sim_free-china-weekly_1982-01-03_23_1/page/n2/
|passage=The Chinese Communists destroyed natural resources by widening the '''Yangtze''' River, and brought natural disasters to the mainland, including the worst floods in [[Szechwan]] province and other areas. }}
#* {{quote-journal |en |url=https://archive.org/details/time-magazine-3-august-2020/ |date=2020 August 10 |title=Worst Rains in Decades Cause China Flooding |journal={{w|Time (magazine)|Time}} |volume=196 |issue=5-6 |page=10 |pageurl=https://archive.org/details/time-magazine-3-august-2020/page/10/
